  "response": "Here are several methods to differentiate water from other liquid solvents using ice:\n\n1. Freezing Point\n- Water freezes at 0\u00b0C (32\u00b0F)\n- Other liquids have different freezing points\n- Compare freezing temperatures to identify the substance\n\n2. Density Characteristics\n- Water expands when freezing (unlike most liquids)\n- Ice floats on liquid water\n- Different liquids may show different density behaviors\n\n3. Melting Behavior\n- Water ice melts at a consistent temperature (0\u00b0C)\n- Other liquids might have varied melting characteristics\n- Observe melting rate and temperature\n\n4. Crystal Structure\n- Water forms distinctive hexagonal crystal structures\n- Use microscopic observation to examine ice crystal patterns\n- Different liquids produce different crystal formations\n\n5. Thermal Conductivity\n- Ice conducts heat differently compared to other frozen liquids\n- Measure heat transfer rates during melting\n\n6. Optical Properties\n- Water ice has specific light refraction properties\n- Use polarized light to examine crystal structure\n- Different liquids show varying optical characteristics\n\n7. Electrical Conductivity\n- Frozen water can conduct electricity differently\n- Compare electrical properties of ice from various liquids\n\nThese methods provide systematic approaches to distinguish water from other liquid solvents using ice.",
